4 and 5 have been written alongside 2 and 3. 2 and 3 were produced simultaneously as they were originally a single story that was way too expansive for one film (think of everything that was included in TWOW and how much was cut out + multiple new clans and environments in 3.) I think they had the right idea of splitting up the films, that way TWOW serves as an audience reintroduction to the world + lays foundation for the rest of the saga in one movie. 3 is supposedly a lot darker and features malevolent Na'vi. The sully kids are only children/teens in this 2 film chapter.

4 and 5 on the other hand were written as their own self sustained chapters and will feature Lo'ak, Kiri, Tuk, Tsireya and Spider + a 6 year time skip; this means Lo'ak, Kiri and Tsireya will be fully grown Na'vi and Tuk will be Kiri's age in TWOW. Will definitely be interested to see how these characters act with more experience on them (not to mention the actors themselves who are mostly newcomers.) I'm definitely looking forward to see how Jack Champion plays Spider after a few years.

Obviously there's a lot Cameron could do with an anticipated 6 year time skip - including the production of new Avatars/Recoms... Not to mention all the Earth scenes supposedly in 4 and 5.

Either way Cameron has gone on the record stating if they end the current saga on 3 due to poor performance of 2 that they will leave the other films on the back burner with intentions to eventually continue. Maybe after a Terminator movie or Battle Angel 2.

There is never hardcore sex in mainstream cinema, aside from the occasional foreign or indie arthouse flick. "Hardcore" specifically means non-simulated sex acts depicted explicitly. That never happens in major studio films, if for no other reasons than because it's contrary to SAG rules and besides that it would automatically draw, at best, the dreaded NC-17 rating from the MPA. Sex scenes which are effectively nothing more than *softcore* porn have indeed become quite common in movies and more especially on premium TV in the last couple of decades (even while the softcore side of the conventional porn business was in the process of dying out). >>178431549
>what films should be about
Every filmmaker has a different set of priorities.
Some have a story fully-formed in their mind, almost writing itself, and they're desperate to transfer it to the screen. Whether the viewer likes it or not is almost a secondary consideration.
Some consider themselves to be in a position of responsibility. They feel like their work should represent the changes they wish to see in the world, and/or to convince the viewer of various real-world viewpoints.
Some want to explore the raw power of cinema and try to instil the strongest emotions (positive and negative) in the viewer that they can, by whatever means necessary.
Some prioritise general entertainment value and set out to make fun, exciting movies for everyone to enjoy.
Some just want to make as much money as possible.
For most, it's a weighted combination of the above.

All types of film have their place in the world. However, if you set me up to expect a certain kind of storytelling experience, and then it turns out that your priorities actually lie elsewhere, I might feel tricked and I might come away from your film with an unfavourable impression of it.

>>178432222
Yeah that was the best part of the ending, it's both the outcast kids that feel like they don't belong (and the two who have 5 fingers on their hands instead of 4) that end up rescuing their parents. I think it's incredibly impactful precisely because loak gets his father to believe in himself, tells him "you can do this dad" (and then the scene cuts to kiri going "trust me", which is just a perfect edit) and then he and Jake make it out with the help of his whale buddy. Jake acknowledging him after that hit way harder than I'd the ending had just been Jake telling loak to believe in himself out of nowhere. Reminds me of how God of War Ragnarok flipped the tables by having Atreus be the one to take care of his dad instead of having kratos shoulder all the burdens on their journey by himself, so then when kratos tells atreus that the reason they won was because of the choices that atreus made, it feels like a much greater victory.

I think it's nice because you don't get the sense that the story was made by someone that sought a coddling narrative that would double as therapy for people with a chip on their shoulder any never having been appreciated by their parents. Cameron comes across like someone that understands both young people as well as parents incredibly well, so seeing the kids actually earn the respect of their parents feels really moving.

>>178437565
Yes, it's a three hour movie where style, aesthetic, and immersion are given a huge amount of focus. The screenplay exists in service of the movie as a whole, and it is enormously successful on basically all fronts. I'm not comparing it to Chinatown. That would be stupid. For what it is, for what it's trying to do, and for what it succeeds at, I absolutely believe it's one of the best screenplays ever written. Avatar 2 does an absolute shitload in terms of story and characters and people that are dismissing it as simple because it uses established frameworks or character arcs are actually missing the complexity because of how well everything is pulled off. Avatar 2 is like a Beach Boys song in the respect. It can seem simple as you experience it, but that's because it's melding an incredible array of components together so well that all of the individual achievements aren't shoved in your face and it becomes so seamless as to appear childlike. The movie as a whole is absolutely masterful.

It's not awful but still pretty bad, though enjoyable.
A good score, a handful of based characters, decent cinematography and nice visuals (for the time) don't make up for all the bullshit we get to see on screen.
Nick is the second most despicable piece of shit in the entire franchise, worse than anyone even in Jurassic World clone girl from TFK is the worst.
It's also one of the first films with actual forced diversity, furthermore it cut out the main antagonist's death from the book which was absolutely great writing, there are no camouflaging Carnos, and somehow gymnastics kill raptors but big guns don't (to be fair, guns never doing shit is an issue with all the films, but never present in the books).
But credit where credit's due, it had its tense moments and memorable quotes from Roland Tembo.
San Diego scene felt "detached" from the rest of the movie, but was masterfully done given it was a last minute change.
What I find most annoying is the forced eco-shit message and the fact that the three main asshole characters don't get eaten halfway through to leave room for Tembo and his hunt for a Rex buck.
Overall it's a mess and it is a miracle it was even enjoyable to watch when it came out.

I'm in no hurry to rewatch this any time soon.

Adding onto what these guys said:
The reason why GoW Ragnarok is often lumped together with the not-capeshit-but-still-goyslop crowd is that it has the same writing issues you see permeate a lot of popular media.
The dialogue is very irreverent, jokey, and dripping in irony. Marvelspeak and Whedonspeak are abused to absurd levels and it ruins tension in many scenes.
The story is supposed to be serious (it's about ragnarok, so of course), but characters act like everything is a joke and no one takes anything seriously. There are more noticeable comic relief moments peppered throughout the game that feels like a shallow attempt to appeal to broader, younger audiences.
The hero of the story, Kratos, has like no agency in the story. The big problem with the game is that there's too many 'protagonists' and the writers cant seem to decide who is actually the main character or whose journey is most important. Kratos has no agency and just reacts to things happening around him that are out of his control. Atreus is roped into a separate journey far away from Kratos but he is a whiny teen dipshit and is not compelling at all as a protag. Freya is also given a lot of attention in the story and a lot of the story is focused on building up her confrontation with Odin, even though she isn't the main character. Too much shit happening with no clear focus.
The villain, Odin, is a subversive take on the evil mastermind, but the writers failed because instead of making him actually unique or subversive, he just comes across as some pathetic Woody Allen esque new york jew that you cannot take seriously as a threat, even at his absolute worst or menacing. The character is just a pitiful old man and doesn't work as a menacing villain you're motivated to defeat.
I also haven't mentioned the other smaller but important issues, like the stupid sidequests and plots that go absolutely nowhere, the rushed final act that neatly ties up everything, etc.
